Right-wing populists win in Austria, 29 percent overall
The first preliminary results show a marked weakening of the two parties in the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties in the Austrian parliamentary elections scheduled for Sunday.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, has been seriously shaken, suffered particularly heavy losses.
In contrast, the president of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the regional governor of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing to return to national politics with a victory.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the country's strongest party with 29.8% of the vote, but has lost 5.5% of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
The situation is even worse for the ÖVP, which loses nearly nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
Both of these major parties have achieved the worst results in Austria's post-war history, and the result is literally catastrophic for the People's Party, which has led to early elections.
In early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a significant advantage over the SPÖ according to opinion polls.
But the voters were visibly punished for letting the government fail.
The first reactions to the results have already led to speculation about the possible resignation of party chairman Wilhelm Molterer, the current vice-chancellor.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the party leadership.
This development is likely to facilitate the increasingly likely exit from the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ-ÖVP grand coalition.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ) had previously won 18% of the vote and the BZÖ 11% - the Social Democrats expressed their fears that the same situation as in 1999 would not be repeated when the People's Party agreed to a joint government with the populists (the FPÖ was still united at the time, having split from the BZÖ in 2005), which even led to sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared his willingness to cooperate with any party, and I assume he can return to Vienna in national politics, is obviously looking for this solution.
The Greens also entered parliament, but they lost some of their popularity and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties crossed the four percent threshold and did not get into parliament.
