Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey was even considering joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps only 20 paces from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial quest.
Hydarpasha Railway Station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the travel books say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, with a tower at each front corner, and looks like some German country townhouse.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's getting a little bit dizzy.
However, from the inside of the department store, it is clear that this was the westernmost gateway to a large enterprise.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, the "late future" of conquest, wanted to realize its ambitions to conquer the Middle East with this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to what is now Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railroad was attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army had withdrawn from Egypt and had driven the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderabad station was no better.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded, destroying the building's beautifully designed roof.
Turkish sources say there was sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling into disrepair and has largely outlived history.
At the same time, today, as a railway gateway to Anatolia and the entire Eastern region, Turkey serves as an expanding diplomatic horizon, at least in a symbolic sense.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to measure the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded a night train to Ankara, the Turkish capital, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish parliamentarian, Suat Kiniklioglut.
The next morning, after about 10:30 hours of darkness, which at the time gave the beat to the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, the new city being a symbol of the new secular state that turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone-and-steel building, specifically designed for this purpose, in a developing suburban area, between half-finished shopping malls and coffee houses, where the middle-managers in suits, both men and women, meet to make deals in the early morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right-of-center politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy objective is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War upset the order", he said.
Turkey is isolated from the hinterland.
Today, he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He didn't have a choice.
It had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will be forced to choose?"
"Turkey never wanted to be left with a back door".
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here has almost mechanically repeated: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea surrounding countries are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey itself.
It's like they're trying to convey the message that, figuratively, with Turkey, all of Europe can get to Asia and the Middle East on those eastern railroads.
When I was back at Hydarpasha Station, after another mostly awake night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conur, the two German gentlemen who had watched this magnificent structure being built 100 years ago.
How would they have been surprised to learn that Europe's Middle East ambitions are now largely in the hands of Turkey?
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back across the Bosporus, I remembered that at the time Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
At least back then, there was no question as to which continent would claim this exciting country.
