The collision avoidance "honeymoon"
To develop accident-prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
A Japanese company has designed a robot that mimics the roar of bees to avoid accidents.
It may be that a device called Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C will be the first step in developing collision-prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technology Center in collaboration with the renowned Advanced Science and Technology Research Center at the University of Tokyo, Japan, built this little robot.
According to Kazuhhiro Doi, Brand Director of Technology PR and Research Development, the BR23C is a further extension of Nissan's four-level safety casing.
The robot is enhancing the collision avoidance capabilities of the company's products.
Each bee develops its own oval-shaped personal space in flight, which is very similar to the Nissan safety jacket.
But far more important is the complex eye of the bee, which allows it to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing it to fly freely in its own personal space.
To mimic the complex function of the eye, engineers designed a device called a laser range finder.
The instrument shall identify obstacles within a 180-degree field of view of up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C, calculate their distance and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor which is immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
"Once the obstacle is detected, the robot immediately changes direction by mimicking the bee's movements, moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid a collision.
The system is most distinguished from the instruments currently available in that the evasive manoeuvre is carried out completely automatically.
Without this, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the evasive maneuver cannot be upward or downward or transverse, but only in two dimensions and only in the direction of the invertibility of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and manner as in the case of bees.
That's why Nissan has added a rotation function to the robot, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
No need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can operate without interruption with only a few dozen KB of memory.
Now, this may sound surprising, but it's not really gigabytes, but we're not even talking about megabyte-sized memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be available in series production cars within ten years.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, further applications may include the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to get the car to its final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
